<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="ic-4-sample" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>IC-4 Sample Outcomes</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 40 minutes to complete 1 problem 
        with parts. For these you will be asked to set up all three problems but only 
        asked to fully evaluate one. Here are samples of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <page>
    <exercise>
        <introduction><p>Let the lamina <m>R</m> be bounded by the <m>x=1-y^2</m> and 
            the y-axis. Let <m>\rho(x,y)=12x</m> <m>mg/cm^2</m></p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Sketch the lamina <m>R</m>.</p></statement>
            <answer><image width="60%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                            label="prefigure-ic4-sample">
                <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                <coordinates bbox="(-2,-2,2,2)">
                    <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    <path start="(0,-1)" stroke="blue" fill="lightgray">
                    <arc center="(0,0)" radius="1" range="(-90,90)"/>
                    <lineto point="(0,-1)"/>
                    </path>
                    <label anchor="(0.5,0)"><m>D</m></label>
                </coordinates>
                <annotations>
                    text="D is the right half of the unit-circle.">
                    <annotation ref="graph-f"
                                text="D is the right half of the unit-circle."/>
                </annotations>
                </diagram>
                </prefigure>
            </image></answer>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Compute the mass of the lamina <m>R</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the mass, integrate the density function over the region <m>R</m>.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>mass=\frac{32}{5}</m> grams</p></answer>
            <solution><p>Based on the graph of the region <m>R</m>, we can see that the limits on the 
                integral will be <m>0 \leq x \leq 1-y^2</m> and <m>-1 \leq y \leq 1</m>.</p>
            <p>So the mass integral is:</p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x dA = \int_{-1}^{1} \int_{0}^{1-y^2} 12x dx dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x dA = \int_{-1}^{1} \left[6x^2\right]_0^{1-y^2} dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x dA = \int_{-1}^{1} 6(1-y^2)^2 dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x dA = \int_{-1}^{1} 6(1-2y^2+y^4) dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x dA = \int_{-1}^{1} 6-12y^2+6y^4 dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x dA = \left[6y-4y^3+\frac{6}{5}y^5\right]_{-1}^{1} dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x dA = 6(1)-4(1)+\frac{6}{5}(1) - (6(-1)-4(-1)+\frac{6}{5}(-1)))</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x dA = \frac{32}{5}</m> grams</p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Without calculation, explain why <m>M_x = 0</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Think about the symmetry of the region <m>R</m> with respect to the <m>x</m>-axis.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>The region <m>R</m> is symmetric about the <m>x</m>-axis, so the first moment about 
                the <m>x</m>-axis is zero.</p></answer>
            <solution><p><m>M_x</m> measures the tendency of the lamina to rotate about the <m>x</m>-axis. Here 
                the density function depends only on <m>x</m>, so the mass is distributed symmetrically above 
                and below the <m>x</m>-axis. Since the region <m>R</m> is symmetric about the <m>x</m>-axis, 
                the first moment about the <m>x</m>-axis is zero.</p></solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Compute the center of mass of the lamina <m>R</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the formulas for the center of mass coordinates. Calculate the moment about the <m>y</m>-axis.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>M_y=\frac{128}{5}</m> grams</p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the moment about the <m>y</m>-axis, we integrate <m>x</m> times the density function over the 
                region <m>R</m>. Using the same limits (region) as before we get:</p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x^2 dA = \int_{-1}^{1} \int_{0}^{1-y^2} 12x^2 dx dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x^2 dA = \int_{-1}^{1} \left[4x^3\right]_0^{1-y^2} dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x^2 dA = \int_{-1}^{1} 4(1-y^2)^3 dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x^2 dA = \int_{-1}^{1} 4(1-3y^2+3y^4-y^6) dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x^2 dA = \int_{-1}^{1} 4-12y^2+12y^4-4y^6 dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x^2 dA = \left[4y-4y^3+\frac{12}{5}y^5-\frac{4}{7}y^7\right]_{-1}^{1} dy</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x^2 dA = 4(1)-4(1)+\frac{12}{5}(1) - (4(-1)-4(-1)+\frac{12}{5}(-1)))</m></p>
            <p><m>\iint_R 12x^2 dA = \frac{128}{5}</m> grams</p></solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction><p>Given the thin plate of the constant density <m>\rho=5</m> modeled 
            by the plane region <m>R:</m> The rectangle <m>[-2,1]]\times\left[1,3]</m></p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the center of mass of the lamina <m>R</m>.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Set up the integrals for the moments and the mass using the limits of the rectangle.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>\left(\frac{M_y}{M}, \frac{M_x}{M}\right) = \left(0, 2\right)</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>First find the mass:</p>
            <p><m>M = \iint_R \rho dA = 5 \iint_R dA</m></p>
            <p><m>M = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \int_1^3 dy dx</m></p>
            <p><m>M = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \left[y\right]_1^3 dx</m></p>
            <p><m>M = 5 \int_{-2}^1 2 dx</m></p>
            <p><m>M = 10 \left[x\right]_{-2}^1</m></p>
            <p><m>M = 10 (3) = 30</m> grams</p>
            <p>Next, find the moment about the <m>y</m>-axis:</p>
            <p><m>M_y = \iint_R x \rho dA = 5 \iint_R x dA</m></p>
            <p><m>M_y = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \int_1^3 x dy dx</m></p>
            <p><m>M_y = 5 \int_{-2}^1 x \left[y\right]_1^3 dx</m></p>
            <p><m>M_y = 5 \int_{-2}^1 2x dx</m></p>
            <p><m>M_y = 5 \left[x^2\right]_{-2}^1</m></p>
            <p><m>M_y = 5 (1 - 4) = -15</m></p>
            <p>Finally, find the moment about the <m>x</m>-axis:</p>
            <p><m>M_x = \iint_R y \rho dA = 5 \iint_R y dA</m></p>
            <p><m>M_x = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \int_1^3 y dx dy</m></p>
            <p><m>M_x = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \left[\frac{y^2}{2}\right]_1^3 dx</m></p>
            <p><m>M_x = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \frac{1}{2} (9 - 1) dx</m></p>
            <p><m>M_x = 5 \int_{-2}^1 4 dx</m></p>
            <p><m>M_x = 20 \left[x\right]_{-2}^1</m></p>
            <p><m>M_x = 20 (3) = 60</m></p>
            <p>Thus, the center of mass is at <m>\left(\frac{M_y}{M}, \frac{M_x}{M}\right) = \left(0, \frac{60}{30}\right) = \left(0, 2\right)</m>.</p>
        </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Find the moments of inertia.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Set up the integrals for the moments of inertia using the limits of the rectangle.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>I_x = 130</m>, <m>I_y = 30</m>, and <m>I_0 = 160</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the moments of inertia, we use the formulas:</p>
            <p><m>I_x = \iint_R (y^2) \rho dA</m></p>
            <p><m>I_y = \iint_R (x^2) \rho dA</m></p>
            <p><m>I_0 = I_x + I_y</m></p>
            <p>Using the same limits as before:</p>
            <p><m>I_x = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \int_1^3 y^2 dy dx</m></p>
            <p><m>I_x = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \left[\frac{y^3}{3}\right]_1^3 dx</m></p>
            <p><m>I_x = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \frac{1}{3} (27 - 1) dx</m></p>
            <p><m>I_x = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \frac{26}{3} dx</m></p>
            <p><m>I_x = \frac{130}{3} \left[x\right]_{-2}^1</m></p>
            <p><m>I_x = \frac{130}{3} (1 - (-2)) = \frac{130}{3} (3) = 130</m></p>
            <p><m>I_y = 5 \int_{-2}^1 \int_1^3 x^2 dx dy</m></p>
            <p><m>I_y = 5 \int_{-2}^1 x^2 \left[y\right]_1^3 dy</m></p>
            <p><m>I_y = 5 \int_{-2}^1 2x^2 dy</m></p>
            <p><m>I_y = 10 \int_{-2}^1 x^2 dx</m></p>
            <p><m>I_y = 10 \left[\frac{x^3}{3}\right]_{-2}^1</m></p>
            <p><m>I_y = 10 \frac{1}{3} (1 - (-8)) = 10 \frac{9}{3} = 30</m></p>
            <p><m>I_0 = I_x + I_y = 130 + 30 = 160</m></p>
        </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
  </worksheet>